 have subfolders. inside asio, there should be an include folder: c:/includes/asio/include. g++ main.cpp -i\"c:/includes/asio/include\" -i\"c:/includes/crow/include\" -lws2_32 -lmswsock -o app.exe this will generate .\\app.exe. run it: you‚Äôll see this: .\\app.exe (2025-06-20 03:58:29) [info ] crow/master server is running at   using 2 threads (2025-06-20 03:58:29) [info ] call `app.loglevel(crow::loglevel::warning)` to hide info level logs. it suggests accessing   in your browser, but this may fail. instead, visit:   the address 0.0.0.0 is a placeholder meaning \"all network interfaces\"‚Äîso the server listens on all your computer‚Äôs interfaces, but it‚Äôs not a valid ip to access directly in a browser. you‚Äôll see this message in the browser: to stop the server, press ctrl + c in the terminal. everything is working! i‚Äôve been doing many things with crow, like this tasks++/todo++ using crow c++, databases, htmx, and tailwindcss: üé• watch the video   for more information, visit:", "nouns": ["crow", "window", "web", "application", "crow", "c++", "framework", "http", "web", "service", "websocket", "flask", "python", "information", "video", "crow", "crow", "documentation", "conan", "vcpkg", "package", "manager", "c++", "user", "article", "crow", "window", "scratch", "tool", "system", "link", "installation", "tutorial", "window", "git", "python", "gcc", "clang", "winget", "powershell", "command", "install", "--id", "git.git", "--source", "winget", "winget", "install", "--id", "kitware.cmake", "install", "--id", "martinstorsjo.llvm", "winget", "install", "--id", "python.python.3.11", "machine", "gcc", "tutorial", "note", "cmake", "mingw", "folder", "version", "compatibility", "cmake", "example", "get", "command", "cmake", "terminal", "path", "command", "cmake", "commandtype", "name", "version", "source", "application", "c:\\mingw64\\bin\\cmake.exe", "installation", "kitware", "example", "item", "-path", "disabled-cmake.exe", "get", "command", "cmake", "path", "c: